[[File:Porto_de_Lisboa_(2).jpg|thumb|Port of [[Lisbon]], [[Portugal]]]]
The '''Port of Lisbon''' ([[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]: ''Porto de Lisboa'') is the third largest [[port]] in [[Portugal]], located where the [[River Tagus]] and the [[Atlantic Ocean]] meet, in the Portuguese capital of [[Lisbon]]. Due to its strategic location on the Portuguese coast between Europe, Africa, and the Atlantic, the port is one of the most accessed and utilized in [[Europe]], and is close to the [[cruise ships]] terminals.


==History==
There are data on human presence in the Tagus estuary since prehistory. Probably the [[Phoenicians]] were in this area in the 12th Century BC and they would create a commercial port in the north margin of the [[River Tagus]].{{fact|date=October 2017}} In 205 BC, the city (known as ''Olissippo'') was conquered by the [[Romans]]. In the 5th Century the [[Suebi]] conquered the area, followed by the [[Visigoths]]. In AD 714, the [[Moors]] conquered Lisbon, expanding the port with their [[Mediterranean]] and Atlantic trades.

